Women vs - The mission was to create a stereo type that would last through the ages. One that exists even today with help from people like Lee Daniels & Danny Strong During the era of the Jim Crow laws, it was a crime for Blacks to argue with White people, Black women were given a leeway to which was not only supposed to represent their acceptance into White families as â€œmammies? This stereotype portrays Black women as not only offering help to the White families but it also showcases Black women with anger and masculinity. Many movie producers today keep this stereotype alive in order to influence younger woman that this is how are supposed to act. Tyler Perry for example: He showcases himself as a Black woman, Madea. Madea is portrayed as a big, black, strong, hostile and sometimes illogical woman who has the tendency to overreact with force and violence when she has been wronged or wants to defend herself. She is also portrayed as extremely nurturing and cares a lot about the well-being of children and teenagers but never hesitant to â€œlash out?on them anytime they showed signs of disrespect. She involves herself in the situations of others, giving them advice and offering self-defense tips or methods of vengeance when needed. Moreover, her hospitality is overridden by her comical aggressiveness demonstrated more to the audience which adds to the false depiction of Black women. On the other hand, Lee Daniels and Danny Strongâ€™s television show, Empire, is another example of the stereotype of the trope of angry Black woman. In fact, one of the main characters, Cookie Lyon is an embodiment of the stereotype Black women face in the film. This show represents a tough motherly figure who was born and raised in the â€œhood?around drug dealers and gangs. She served 17 years in prison, away from her children and did not get to watch them grow up. She along with her husband, Lucious Lyons, were fortunate enough to form a company known as Empire, which took them from rags to riches. The elegance can be seen through what she wears with knee-high boots, fashionable fur coats, long color-coded nails, but her short temper and violent tendencies tend to overshadow her good. Black women continue to be affected by this stereotype, in the sense that people who have been conditioned to view African American women as angry Black women, respond to Black womenâ€™s emotions with fear. With this trope as one of the biggest topics and issues in Black film, and the lack of diversity of Black women in film which can leave an impression on the audience that Black women are all always angry. We must set aside these stereotypes and Black Women today need to grab hold instead of the qualities that our Father in heaven declares are righteous. Considering where our city is today I did not expect to be inspired the way I was when by some quirk of fate I got a chance to visit Raj Bhavin, the Governorâ€™s estate at Walkeshwar earlier this week. We truly felt like guests as we were escorted around the estate by the warm and courteous Raj Bhavan team. The estate itself is sprawled over 46 acres and by their records has over 3000 different trees. There were several peacocks and many varieties of birds. And everything is immaculately maintained. As we sat at the sunrise point and experienced the sunrise we were mesmerised by the stunning scene that unfolded. That entire moment and the estate truly showed us what Mumbai was like in the past and honestly what itâ€™s potential is. This was that moment of inspiration. We as Mumbaikars can expect to get our city back and drive the powers that be to revive and recreate the city the way it was. G & I chose to walk around and take in the green experience. This was truly invigorating despite the summer heat. It is very special to be ensconced in greenery within the city. This little forest in the heart of the city lifted our spirits. Getting up at 4.30, showering and reaching the Raj Bhavan gate 5.45 am was quite a challenge. But in hindsight I am really glad that we did it. The experience was truly surreal and inspiring.
